d  . This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Rachford","meanings":["English:","variant of   Rochford  .","variant of<b>Rackford</b>, a habitational name from Rackenford in Devon,recorded in Domesday Book as <i>Racheneforda</i>, which Millsinterprets as ‘ford suitable for riding, by a stretch of river’."]},{"name":"Ratchford","meanings":["habitational name from Rochford (Worcestershire), from Old English <i>ræcc</i> ‘hunting dog’ (genitive <i>ræcces</i>) + <i>ford</i> ‘ford’.","habitational name from Rochford (Essex). Early forms of the name ending in <i>Ro-</i> suggest that the placename derives from Old English <i>hrōc</i> ‘rook’ or the Old English personal name <i>Hrōc(a)</i> + Old English <i>ford</i> ‘ford’, but the 13th century forms in <i>Ra-</i> and <i>Re-</i> suggest that the first element is Old English <i>ræcc</i> ‘hunting dog’.","English:"]},{"name":"Rotchford","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Caitlin.","Irish and English: variant of   Rochford  ."]}]},{"name":"Ralph","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From a Norman French name, <i>Raulf</i>, a contracted form of the Germanic personal name <i>Radulf</i>, derived from <i>rād</i> ‘counsel’ + <i>wulf</i> ‘wolf’. The spelling with <i>-ph</i> is due to classical influence in the 18th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Ralf","meanings":["From a Norman French name, <i>Raulf</i>, a contracted form of the Germanic personal name <i>Radulf</i>, derived from <i>rād</i> ‘counsel’ + <i>wulf</i> ‘wolf’. The spelling with <i>-ph</i> is due to classical influence in the 18th century."]}]},{"name":"Ii","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Violet  ,   Vivien  , or   Vivian ."],"variants":[{"name":"Vivien","meanings":["Earlier generally taken as a variant of the boy's name   Vivian  , but now also rarely used for boys. This spelling was quite common in Old French. Its use as a girl's name in the English-speaking world was influenced by  Tennyson's  Merlin and Vivien (  1859 ). This name, from Arthurian legend, may represent an altered form of a Celtic name (perhaps akin to the Irish Gaelic name <i>Béibhinn</i> ‘white lady’, pronounced ‘bee-<b>veen</b>’). The actress  Vivien Leigh  (  1913–67 ) was christened <i>Vivian</i>."]},{"name":"Violet","meanings":["From the name of the flower (Old French <i>violette</i>, Late Latin <i>violetta</i>, a diminutive of <i>viola</i>). This was one of the earliest flower names to become popular in Britain, being used as early as  1700  and becoming well established in the 19th century, although it is now somewhat out of favour."]},{"name":"Vivian","meanings":["Originally a boy's name, from an Old French form of the Latin name <i>Vivianus</i> (probably a derivative of <i>vivus</i> ‘alive’), but now more frequent as a girl's name. The name was borne by a 5th-century bishop of Saintes in western France, remembered for protecting his people during the invasion of the Visigoths."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Ralph Ii Rochford was born in 1280, in Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom as the son of John I Rochford. He had at least 1 son with Anne."},"et":{"1280–":"1280–Surnud","1280–Male":"1280–Surnud","1282–Female":"1282–Surnud","1320–1350":"1320–1350","1250–Male":"1250–Surnud","1320":"1320","1350":"1350","1250":"1250","1282":"1282","abt 1320":"umbes 1320","1280":"1280","Fenn in Boston, Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Boston, Lincolnshire, England":"Boston, Lincolnshire, England"},"fi":{"1280–":"1280–Kuollut","1280–Male":"1280–Kuollut","1282–Female":"1282–Kuollut","1320–1350":"1320–1350","1250–Male":"1250–Kuollut","1320":"1320","1350":"1350","1250":"1250","1282":"1282","abt 1320":"noin 1320","1280":"1280","Fenn in Boston, Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Boston, Lincolnshire, England"